      </div>
      <h1 class='title'>Circumstances in which orders under this Part may be made</h1>
    </div>
    <div class='grand-committee-report-sitting' id='content'>
      
      <cite class='section'>HL Deb 17 May 2004 vol 661 cc270-1GC</cite>
      <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_270gc' title='Col. 270GC &mdash; HL Deb 17 May 2004 vol 661 c270GC' name='column_270gc' href='#column_270gc' rel='bookmark'>270GC</a>
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0661P0-03603'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0661P0_20040517_GCR_211' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        1(1) The court may make any one or more of the orders set out in paragraph 2(1)&#x2014;
        <ol>
        <li>(a) on making a dissolution, nullity or separation order, or</li>
        <li>(b) at any time afterwards.</li></ol>
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0661P0-03604'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0661P0_20040517_GCR_212' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        (2) The court may make any one or more of the orders set out in paragraph 2(1)(d), (e) and (f)&#x2014;
        <ol>
        <li>(a) in proceedings for a dissolution, nullity or separation order, before making the order;</li>
        <li>(b) if proceedings for a dissolution, nullity or separation order are dismissed after the beginning of the trial, either straightaway or within a reasonable period after the dismissal.</li></ol>
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0661P0-03605'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0661P0_20040517_GCR_213' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        (3) The power of the court to make an order under subparagraph (1) or (2)(a) in favour of a child of the family is exercisable from time to time.
      </p>
      
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0661P0-03606'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0661P0_20040517_GCR_214' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        (4) If the court makes an order in favour of a child under subparagraph (2)(b), it may from time to time make a further order in the child's favour of any of the kinds set out in paragraph 2(1)(d), (e) or (f).
      </p>
      <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_271gc' title='Col. 271GC &mdash; HL Deb 17 May 2004 vol 661 c271GC' name='column_271gc' href='#column_271gc' rel='bookmark'>271GC</a>
      <p class='procedural' id='S5LV0661P0-03607'>
        <a class='permalink' href='#S5LV0661P0_20040517_GCR_215' title='Link to this contribution' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
        (5) If the court makes an order under sub-paragraph (1), (2) or (4), it may give such consequential directions as it thinks fit for giving effect to the order (including directions requiring the disposal of any property).
      </p>
      <ol class='xoxo'>
        
